05673nam a22007695i 9780231549097DE-B159720230127011820.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230127t20202020nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802315490977 a10.7312/low-190762doi  a(DE-B1597)575757  a(OCoLC)1140354108  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aBP187.3b.L69 2020 7aHIS0550002bisacsh04a297.3/5242231 aLow, Michael Christopher, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aImperial Mecca :bOttoman Arabia and the Indian Ocean Hajj /cMichael Christopher Low. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aColumbia Studies in International and Global History00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tA Note on Sources, Transliteration, and Dates -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction Between Two Worlds An Ottoman Island Adrift on a Colonial Ocean -- tPART ONE Extraterritorial Frontiers -- tONE Blurred Vision The Hijaz and the Hajj in the Colonial Imagination -- tTWO Legal Imperialism Foreign Muslims and Muslim Consuls -- tPART TWO Ecologies of Empire -- tTHREE Microbial Mecca and the Global Crisis of Cholera -- tFOUR Bedouins and Broken Pipes -- tPART THREE Managing Mobility -- tFIVE Passports and Tickets -- tSIX The Camel and the Rail -- tEpilogue Legacies and Afterlives -- tNotes -- tAbbreviations -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWith the advent of the steamship, repeated outbreaks of cholera marked oceanic pilgrimages to Mecca as a dangerous form of travel and a vehicle for the globalization of epidemic diseases. European, especially British Indian, officials also feared that lengthy sojourns in Arabia might expose their Muslim subjects to radicalizing influences from anticolonial dissidents and pan-Islamic activists. European colonial empires’ newfound ability to set the terms of hajj travel not only affected the lives of millions of pilgrims but also dramatically challenged the Ottoman Empire, the world’s only remaining Muslim imperial power.Michael Christopher Low analyzes the late Ottoman hajj and Hijaz region as transimperial spaces, reshaped by the competing forces of Istanbul’s project of frontier modernization and the extraterritorial reach of British India’s steamship empire in the Indian Ocean and Red Sea. Imperial Mecca recasts Ottoman Arabia as a distant, unstable semiautonomous frontier that Istanbul struggled to modernize and defend against the onslaught of colonial steamship mobility. As it turned out, steamships carried not just pilgrims, passports, and microbes, but the specter of legal imperialism and colonial intervention. Over the course of roughly a half century from the 1850s through World War I, British India’s fear of the hajj as a vector of anticolonial subversion gradually gave way to an increasingly sophisticated administrative, legal, and medical protectorate over the steamship hajj, threatening to eclipse the Ottoman state and Caliphate’s prized legitimizing claim as protector of Islam’s most holy places. Drawing on a wide range of Ottoman and British archival sources, this book sheds new light on the transimperial and global histories traversed along the pilgrimage to Mecca.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aMuslim pilgrims and pilgrimageszIndian Ocean Region. 0aMuslim pilgrims and pilgrimageszSaudi ArabiazMecca. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / Turkey & Ottoman Empire.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311071097708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe